I have looked a bit into TrueType font rendering, and I think I have some performance improvements, that I would love Daniel's take on. I have run these things through Scout extensively, and each of the fixes yield measurable results.  These changes makes my test case (below) run TWICE as fast on my stationary PC, from 24,1 to 45.9 FPS measured over 60 frames (frame 200-260) in Scout. It would be interesting to know what difference it could make on a mobile device, if any.

The benefits come from caching of state and the BitmapData that Starling uses to render the TrueType text to.

I have identified and improved 3 different areas that each chewed up some time for us:

1) the test to see if we have "drawWithQuality" only needs to be done once.
2) setting embedFont = true and then = false takes a bit of CPU, so only check once per font name. 
3) reusing the BitmapData, if possible.

So, adding this to the class TextField, after the declaration of sNativeTextField:

```
    // some static helpers to reduce runtime checks.
    private static var sHasTestedForDrawWithQuality:Boolean = false;
    private static var sHasDrawWithQuality:Boolean = false;
    private static var sBitmapData:BitmapData = null;
    private static var sEmbedFontNames:Dictionary = new Dictionary();
```

